<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC8FF23FA6B3EC9F997" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" box="[199,973,1519,1546]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="3190DB48FFF9FFC8FF23FA6B3C5DF994" bold="true" box="[199,345,1519,1545]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Description.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity id="C41CAABFFFF9FFC8FE14FA6B3F7EF997" box="[496,634,1519,1546]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" metricValueMax="5.3" metricValueMin="4.3" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="4.8" valueMax="5.3" valueMin="4.3">4.3–5.3 mm</quantity>
; forebody length 
<quantity id="C41CAABFFFF9FFC8FCDBFA6B3ECDF997" box="[831,969,1519,1546]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="2.5" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="2.4">2.4–2.6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC8FF23F9973EA3F9B0" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" box="[199,935,1555,1582]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
Body (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FEF7F9973C53F9B3" box="[275,343,1555,1582]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1933,1957]" captionTargetBox="[161,1436,533,1906]" captionTargetId="figure-159@2.[151,1436,525,1910]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Habitus 1 N. ingentis; 2 N. resimus; 3 N. leigongensis; 4 N. yujiei; 5 N. muricatus; 6 N. excertus; 7 N. serratus. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6554672" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6554672/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) reddish brown; antennae and legs yellowish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC8FF23F9B33C8CF904" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
Head (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FEF6F9B33C67F9CC" box="[274,355,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) 1.00–1.03 times as long as wide; punctation moderately dense and coarse, distinctly umbilicate and partly confluent, interstices with fine microsculpture (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FCC5F9DF3E71F9E8" box="[801,885,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
); postocular portion approximately 1.9–2.1 times as long as eye length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC8FF23F9203ED3F898" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FEA3F9273C9FF920" box="[327,411,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) 1.08–1.10 times as long as wide, 0.93–1.03 times as long and 0.88–0.96 times as broad as head; punctation non-umbilicate, moderately dense, less coarse than that of head; midline posteriorly with very short and narrow impunctate elevation; interstices lacking microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC8FF23F88B3885F8D0" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FEFAF88B3C76F8B4" box="[286,370,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) 0.64–0.68 times as long as wide, 0.53–0.58 times as long and 0.92–0.95 times as broad as pronotum; punctation as dense as, and slightly coarser than that of pronotum; interstices lacking microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC8FF23F8D339D2F80B" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
Abdomen with punctation dense and rather coarse on tergites III–V, dense and less coarse on tergite VI, moderately dense and fine on tergites VII–VIII; with fine microsculpture on all tergites (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FB92F8FF39CDF80B" box="[1142,1225,1915,1942]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF9FFC9FF23F81B3908FF48" blockId="8.[151,1437,1411,2014]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,465]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="50" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
Male. Sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FE7FF81B3CEEF827" box="[411,490,1951,1978]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 36</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin nearly truncate at middle. Sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FB79F81B39E8F824" box="[1181,1260,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
) with triangular posterior excision. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF9FFC8FE03F8473F61F840" box="[487,613,1987,2013]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">Figs 38, 39</figureCitation>
) well sclerotized; ventral process short, dorsal parts slightly widened near apex in ventral view, curved ventrad in lateral view; dorso-lateral apophyses slender, slightly curved and widened in apical third in ventral view, extending much beyond apex of ventral process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4BFE54D1FFF8FFC9FF23FF5A3946FE14" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF8FFC9FF23FF5A3E6BFE80" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="3190DB48FFF8FFC9FF23FF5A3F36FF64" bold="true" box="[199,562,222,249]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Distribution and habitat data.</emphasis>
The species is known from Leigong Mt. in eastern 
<collectingRegion id="C120C9B8FFF8FFC9FB60FF5B39ECFF64" box="[1156,1256,223,249]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
. The specimens were collected by sifting leaf litter at altitudes of 
<quantity id="C41CAABFFFF8FFC9FD5BFE863E6FFE80" box="[703,875,258,285]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.925" metricValueMax="2.15" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="1925.0" valueMax="2150.0" valueMin="1700.0">
<geoCoordinate id="66D0619DFFF8FFC9FD5BFE863FF9FE80" box="[703,765,258,285]" degrees="1,700" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" precision="55" value="1.7">1,700</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="66D0619DFFF8FFC9FD18FE863E4FFE80" box="[764,843,258,285]" degrees="2,150" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" precision="55" value="-2.15">–2,150</geoCoordinate>
m
</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF8FFC9FF23FEA23946FE14" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="3190DB48FFF8FFC9FF23FEA23CB7FEDC" bold="true" box="[199,435,294,321]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
The new species is distinguished from all the known species of 
<taxonomicName id="C4E47CD9FFF8FFC9FB79FEA339F7FEDD" box="[1181,1267,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Nazeris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3190DB48FFF8FFC9FB79FEA339F7FEDD" box="[1181,1267,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Nazeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion id="C120C9B8FFF8FFC9FAD8FEA33898FEDC" box="[1340,1436,295,321]" country="China" name="Guizhou" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Guizhou</collectingRegion>
and adjacent area by the microsculpture present on head and abdomen, and by the distinctive shape of the aedeagus, particularly the short ventral process and the long dorso-lateral apophyses (
<figureCitation id="9BDF1BDFFFF8FFC9FC05FEEB3931FE14" box="[993,1077,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–39" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1768,1792]" captionTargetBox="[153,1424,499,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-144@9.[151,1436,489,1745]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 33–39. Nazeris excertus 33 forebody; 34 ventral surface of head; 35 abdominal tergite V; 36 male sternite VII; 37 male sternite VIII; 38 aedeagus in ventral view; 39 aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 33 1.0 mm; 34–35 0.1 mm; 36–39 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6552233" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6552233/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4BFE54D1FFF8FFC9FF23FE173E17FE4C" pageId="9" pageNumber="50" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="035B075AFFF8FFC9FF23FE173E17FE4C" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,465]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="3190DB48FFF8FFC9FF23FE173C4AFE30" bold="true" box="[199,334,403,429]" pageId="9" pageNumber="50">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet (Latin, adjective: outstretched) alludes to the dorso-lateral apophyses extending strongly beyond apex of ventral process of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
